==English==

===Noun===
{{caterpillar tree}}

In a [[graph theory]], a caterpillar tree is 
a [[tree]], where removal of all end-verteces results in a [[path]]. (Chartrand, G., L. Lesniak. Graphs & Digraphs. Chapman & Hall, London, 1996.) 

Another definition of the same concept says that it is a [[tree]] with a single [[path]] (the spine) that includes or is incident to every edge. (West, Douglas B. . Introduction to Graph Theory. Prentice Hall, Upper Saddle River, 1996.)

Yet a third wording says that it is a [[tree]], in which every vertex is on a central stalk or only one graph edge away from the stalk.

As a consequence, a tree is a caterpillar if, and only if, all nodes with the [[vertex degree]] at least 3 are surrounded 
by at most two nodes of vertex degree two or greater.

The number of caterpillar trees for more than 2 nodes is
C_n==2^(n-4)+2^(|_n/2-2_|),

where |_x_| is the [[floor function]].


In [[botanics]], Caterpillar tree is another name for Catalpa bignonioides (also called Southern Catalpa) of family Bignoniaceae.
It is a deciduous tree growing in Southeastern U.S. and it is the host plant for the catawba worms, caterpillars that are popular fishing bait.

